<br>
<br>
<br>
A couple points (anyone notice we are starting to get a little FV movie review and discussion group going? I love it! I nominate Kurley our leader!)...<br>
<br>
...Ang Lee's use of the paneled screen was by far my favorite element of the film. Two images come to mind: the penultimate scene in which all of the major protagonists and antagonists of the story come together on the Presidio (or whatever base that is supposed to be in SF) in different panels, all the while a still black and white of Nolte's eyes linger in a panel on top of the screen.... beautiful imagery. Also, the moment which the Atheon executive (forgetting his name now) is killed by an errant missile and his body becomes a still image as the explosion continues to be a moving image around him, ultimately enveloping him. What an effective way to convey the power of the scene without resorting to gore or more contrived &quot;realistic CGI&quot;.<br>
<br>
Anyone notice that two of the so-called &quot;Action&quot; films of our blockbuster summer (Hulk and Matrix 2) have been gleefully sacrificed the standard big budget aesthetic of pseudo-realism (think Bruckheimer films, or any film in which an enormous structure explodes with limited collateral damage) and have instead pushed the envelope of the computer generated cinematic image? I know it sounds ludicrous, but some of the experimentation that the Wachowskis and Lee used to tell their tales would likely find a more receptive audience with the arthouse audience than mainstream America, and I think that is why they are suffering with the critics (but these days if you get panned by the NY Times, you must be doing something right... see: Fight Club).<br>
<br>
Finally, anyone notice the almost complete absence of gore in this film? I can think of only two on-screen deaths (the security guard killed by David Banner and Bruce's mother) and recall very little blood being shed. For a movie about a superhuman monsterous anti-hero, Lee handled that part of the film very well I thought, showing amazing restraint.<br>
<br>
What a great summer for film! Next up, 28 Days Later...<br>
